                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top of cover: Illegible text in brown ink.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page in brown ink by a13th century hand, in total 6 lines of text: <quote> Dominus Bruno episcopus olomucensis post consecrationem suam accepit duas precioluces capellas cum pertinenciis pontificalibus...</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1v" to="SL1v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page in brown ink by a modern hand: <quote>Missale R</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>All additions are by a modern hand. Top of page in brown ink: <quote>Kgl. Biblt 1734 års Kat. Theol. in 4o no 18</quote>. Below this in pencil:<quote> Jachesii gamla kat. Ms. in fol. nr 80</quote>. Middle of page in brown ink: <quote>Collectae seu Horae (sine fine)</quote>. Below this in pencil, written by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102536"> Clemens Blume </persName>: <quote>Böhmisk handskrift. Breviarium Bohemicum (Pragense?) saec. 12. Blume</quote>. Lower half of page in left margin in brown ink: <quote>de Sec. xi l. xii</quote>. Bottom of page in right corner in pencil: <quote>A 144</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL2v" to="SL2v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>To the left in pencil by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102536"> Clemens Blume </persName>: the antiphons cited on <locus from="34v" to="34v" scheme="folios"/>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <p>Repaired medieval binding. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> original. Wood covered with pink leather. <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> beech wood, produced in <date when="1974"/>. Two new clasps attached to <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> removed, bookblock and sewing stations exposed. Three double bands (exposed, modern). In the 1850s, the manuscript was resewn on cords, reusing the 13th-century sewing station. The spine and the back cover were then covered with leather. In 1974, <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>, then a pastedown, was removed and raised. The 19th century cover material (with the signum <quote>A 144 </quote>on the spine) is kept in a separate box, together with a dummy of the quires made in 1974.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="290" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="210" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="70" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>Worn, repaired.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100211">Bohemia</placeName>
                                </origPlace>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100212">Olomouc</placeName>
                                </origPlace>
                                <origDate notAfter="1142" notBefore="1136">1136–1142</origDate>. The dating of the manuscript is discussed by <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107235">Bistřický (2011)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="103" to="104" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>, and is based on the table on <locus from="8r" to="8r" scheme="folios"/> as well as the miniature on <locus from="34v" to="34v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Most likely <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100155">St Wenceclas Cathedral</orgName> (Olomouc). <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102548">Bruno of Schauenburg</persName>, bishop of Olomouc 1245-1281, is mentioned in the inscription on <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>The volume was most likely taken as spoils of war during the Thirty Years’ War. In Vossius’ catalogue (ca <date when="1650"/>) (U 202:1), p. 19, mentioned as <quote>Missale Olomucensium</quote>. Also mentioned in Jaches' catalogue from 1698 (U 122), <quote>80</quote>, and the catalogue from 1734 (U 125e), <quote>18</quote>.</p>
                            <p/>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
